The Ukrainian Parliament today refused to abolish, in the context of an amendment to the Criminal Code, the paragraphs on which the opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko had been sentenced.
The new regulation, which could pave the way for the liberation of the imprisoned Prime Minister, rejected the Members at the second reading of the request for the reduction of the penalties for economic offences.
Timoshenko had been sentenced to seven years in prison in October for the conclusion of a allegedly negligent contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not yet juridical, and in December the appeal of the defendants is to be brought before the court.
Timoshenko himself referred to the ruling as political revenge of the regime and also in the West, the trial caused the suspicion of the prejudice of the court.
The request to remove paragraph 365, on the basis of which the Prime Minister was sentenced to remove from the Criminal Code, was supported by 147 Members.
226 votes would have been necessary for its adoption.
