IBM history: from cheese cutter to global flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines) founded in New York a hundred years ago had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Corporation.
The name IBM was only taken over in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for IBM was the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the 80s of the 19th century.
They had technologies such as the famous keycard clocks for registering the beginning and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint became the architect of this new company, which was also chaired by the Supervisory Board by 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competition company Thomas J. Watson to help him manage the company.
This leader even put IBM's founders in the shadows - based on Watson's ideas to this day on the invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson headed the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name already reveals, began to manufacture and distribute all possible machines for the trade - from sausage and cheese cutters to boxes.
In the first four decades, in which Watson led the company, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 60's, technicians and computers from IBM helped steer NASA's flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also to the moon's famous flight.
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC that determined the computer standard of that time came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultancy part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus became fully involved in the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM pays off in the last three years is the concept of "Smarter Planet".
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas that have not even been planned, e.g. to improve the situation in traffic and urban administration.
In the commercial sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smarter Commerce" platform to help dealers manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
As early as 1932, IBM established a branch office in Czechoslovakia - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe at that time.
Today IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague and there is also a top research team of world level that deals with the technology of voice recognition.
