Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorised state travel agencies in the then ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
At the time, the travel agencies sold mainly only trips to the socialist Eastern bloc countries, in the West they were only allowed to choose.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean Peninsula), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia entered a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not even allowed citizens of the Eastern bloc (including Czechoslovakia) to travel freely within the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even at the time, the travel agencies also offered trips to the west, but then you had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" at the travel agency.
Even so, the matter had not been going on for a long time.
The so-called foreign exchange promise - the condition for a trip to the West - was given only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czech currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a foreign exchange commitment it would have been impossible to obtain the necessary funding (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
Thus, the vast majority of Czechs spent their vacation abroad, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dats - a habit that continues to this day.
The 1989 combined revolution followed a travel revolution of the Czechs on foot.
While a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things until 1989, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries all over the world.
A huge paradox, one is no longer aware of today, is the fact that one could not travel to the most popular holiday country in the Czech Republic at all - Croatia until 1989 because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, foreign exchange obligations were abolished in the neighbouring western European countries, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough from their trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
The Czech holidaymakers slept in the park when travelling to Paris, because who would have had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a pension at that time.
A typical feature of travel abroad from Czechs was at that time a suitcase room packed with cans, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the free-exchange Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our level of life and thus the average salaries increased, which resulted in a further important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, the travel agencies began to prepare regular flights through charter flights after 1997, which made it incredibly cheaper thanks to the possibility of negotiating quantity discounts compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, with the exception of the United States, the Czechs had already currencyless payment transactions with all the highly developed countries in the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-total" travel came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand of the first direct charter flight was made into an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, annual direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying in far-away sunny countries; this year, twelve exotic destinations are being flown directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17th, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the world's highly developed countries.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 thousand CZK per capita for a single holiday stay including the cost at the resort.
