After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
That's easy - you just have to log on to Facebook.
"We have found that it was not difficult to come to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the main author of a recently published report by the UK idea factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook's hiding personal data is so encyclopaedic, Bartlett says that the researchers just have to use the advertising tool of the site to precisely determine their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy - as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of extreme right-wing groups all over Europe and then showed them with additions, but instead of linking to a new band or a new diet product, the Adds invited users to a survey asking for their educational status, their attitude toward violence and their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to question more than 10,000 supporters of 14 extremely right parties in 11 European countries - without even having to leave their office once.
"It's a pretty new research method," Bartlett says.
Some of the results hardly surprise. Online promoters of right-wing extreme groups are mostly young, male and annoyed by immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screens."
DEMO's work is just an example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Ideas factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends such as in "Likes", text news and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users who add three content per day on average, Facebook's "Data Supernova" generates a research boom that has increased the number of scientific works with the name of this page in the title by nearly 800% over the last five years.
For some researchers the beauty of Facebook is the fact that one can study through this site people who usually cannot be reached by using their clipboard on the street.
