Climate change slowed the economy
In the first year of Mario López Valdez's government, unemployment and undeclared work rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in Sinaloas’ economic history. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who described himself as the initiator of change and raised great hopes for economic growth, is to the government. However, because of the climatic hardships, growth cannot be the reason, but, on the contrary, the main economic indicators have deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February caused not only losses of millions in agriculture, but also narrow limits to the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity by 3.6 per cent in the first quarter. This mainly stems from the historical decline in agricultural development by 31.16 per cent, which slowed down on other sectors of the economy.
According to a report published by Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Sustainable Agricultural Development Council) on the effects of the frost, 582,000 hectares of land used for agriculture were damaged, 78.03 percent of which were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity by November has caused unemployment to rise continuously in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, as from January to March 55,053 Sinaloas had no employment, corresponding to 4.53 percent of the labour force. In the second quarter the unemployment rate rose to 5,28 percent and from July to September to 6,19 percent, resulting in 74,000 people in Sinaloa. That is 18,969 people more than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in the year dates back to several factors. Economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments that public institutions' policies indirectly explain the growing unemployment rate.
"What we are currently observing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, the loss of liquidity in the market as a result of the cutbacks of legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because it is not easy for those who illegally collect dollars to let them work for themselves, to invest them or to use something else," he explained.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that the growing unemployment rate is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has decreased, on the one hand, due to the entry problems and on the other hand, because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here looking for work that makes unemployment rise," he says.
Undeclared work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if the high proportion of undeclared work is taken into account, which, according to INEGI, includes 60.38 percent of those employed in the country without paying in the social security funds.
The low wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, come to unemployment and undeclared work according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretaria del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Regulatory Authority for Labour and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of employees in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos by September; this is much less than the general government average, which is 7375 pesos.
ADI decline
In addition to reducing economic activity and increasing unemployment, in 2011, the strongest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) over the last ten years is recorded. According to the State Economic Authority, the ADI was 630,597 dollars from January to June, which corresponds to a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 143,312 dollars in the same period of the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Economico del Gobierno (Economic Development Authority) has a total investment of 17,280,000 pesos in 2011, mainly from tertiary companies.
The debts
In view of the economic crisis, the State Government requested a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities in July at the National Congress, but the Landeskongress approved an amount of 200 600 000 pesos, but by November no positive impact of the debt on any of the sectors in the country could be identified.
Reactions
The first year of Mario López Valdé's reign was manifest to representatives of entrepreneurship.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (National Chamber of Manufacturing Industry in Mexico), stated that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise views of different sectors, including the state government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very thirsty this year. It has to be worked hard to regain the terrain lost this year and in 2012 we have to make a double effort. The efforts of all and in particular the progress made by the already well-involved government team have not been sufficiently coordinated," he explained.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events, such as the frost at the beginning of the year, made the country's economic development difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important effects is a slow economy that is not sufficiently moving to produce an economic dynamic that could produce an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore, we will close the year well below our expectations," he said.
redefine appeal
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, Chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Commercial Federation of Mexico) in Sinaloa, declared that the state should be given more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme to redefine the country's economic vocation and line, because it is important to activate all the material and human resources Sinaloas," he said.
There is much to do
The Chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that would improve the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas, but economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas where one can say that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that it has been worked and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
