The Court approved the transition to digital television in Mexico in 2015
The transformation of analogues to digital signals has been among the most important changes in the world in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional lawsuits filed by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the presidential decree and, by virtue of which the switch from analogue to digital signals from 2021 to 2015, due to the lack of eight votes required to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, felt that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his responsibilities when he issued the Decree-Law with the details of switching to terrestrial digital television.
This decision rejected the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate, since it did not receive the required qualified majority of eight votes so that the court could decide on constitutionality or non-constitutionality. Thus, the law remains in force.
In the project for the complaint prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, it was proposed to declare the Legislative Decree unconstitutional, since the regulations concerning radio and television are responsible for the Comisión Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cafetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico), which is why the Decree-Law would contradict hierarchical principles and the law retention.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Representatives filed constitutional complaints against the Decree of the Law. Following the adoption of the lawsuits, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the Decree of the Law and ceased all activities for the establishment of digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the complaint filed by the Chamber of Deputies without entering the debate on the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero was also responsible.
In its contribution, the Prime Minister said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the country government must not regulate the measures to be taken by the public administration with general rules.
"I also do not believe that, if you do, the independence of the regulatory body would be impaired." She also recalled that the central government is responsible for planning strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, because they are the leaders of the state.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes that has taken place throughout the world in recent years, and it results in better use of the radioelectric spectrum, increased signal quality and more channels.
The postponement of the transition, she said, was a postponement of the use of digitalisation, which is a decision in the public interest, which has not only technical aspects, "which include economic, social, political and security aspects."
These issues, she stressed, "needed the whole system to act in accordance with the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a group of features that put the Constitution in the hands of the central government."
She recalled that many countries worldwide had already implemented the digital switchover via the government, although they had highly specialised facilities.
It was not possible to conclude that the government would, with the publication of the contested decree of the law, enter into the powers of the Congress, because the laws adopted by the legislative body would be complied with," she assured.
The possibility of counting the ballots in Michoacán individually is considered
According to PREP, the difference between the first and second place in the election of the governor is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
The possibility of the single counting of the ballots is a reality this year in the elections in Michoacán, because according to the data issued by the Programa de Resultsados Electrices Preliminares (PREP), the difference between the first and second place in the presidential elections is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
In this sense, the president of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, pointed out that just last November, the Electoral Committee adopted a number of rules on the harmonisation of local rules with the reforms of the federal states in electoral matters.
It should be borne in mind that Michoacán had not adapted his political constitution, his electoral law or his electoral law to the reforms adopted by the Congress, so that they had not entered into force at this round of elections. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the state adjudicating officer within the time limits provided for by the Congress with the argument or to object.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) decided on the constitutional complaint filed by the local legislative body and judged the candidate's vote on constitutional reforms as "unlawful and illegal", since he did not have the right to "decide on it or impose a veto against it".
María de los Ángeles Llanderal stated in an interview on the possibility of the single counting of votes that, thanks to the adoption of the directives by the Consejo General del IEM, the local electoral authority could now have partly or completely counted the ballot.
Under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be counted in part The results in the protocols are not consistent; the minutes on the counting and calculation of votes are not available or are not held by the Chairman of the Electoral Committee or there are obvious errors or changes in the protocols.
In addition, if there is a difference between the alleged winner and the person on second place who is equal to or less than one percent, the total number of filled-out ballots may be calculated, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition chairperson, who is the second of the said candidates.
The counting of votes may also take place in its entirety if, upon completion of the ordinary calculation, it is established that the difference between the alleged winner and the candidate in second place is equal or less than one percent, provided that an express request is made by a representative of the party whose second candidate has become. In this case, the electoral packages that were subject to partial counting would be excluded.
It is worth noting that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation, where according to PREP, the difference between the first and second place is close to 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
