Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group of the most powerful emerging and industrialized countries in the world. Since January of this year, there has been an agreement on the exchange of tax information to avoid double settlement with the South American country.
In recent years, the Government of Uruguay has tried to speed up the implementation of agreements on the exchange of tax information to be removed from the "grey list" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), which includes countries that have not introduced all international standards for cooperation in tax matters.
