"This information reinforces the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of the impact."
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points that should be taken into account in the investigation:
Vision flight:
In line with the flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of the visual flight. This means that the team must have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions at the start. During the further flight towards the border area between Mexico City and Mexico State, a few deep- suspended clouds emerged.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that because of the clouds, the team had chosen a lower area with a better view towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Spot-on:
The impact coordinates and the last radar record of the helicopter agree. Perhaps there was neither a loss of control over the aircraft nor a deviation from the flight route prior to the impact.
Disperse the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information provided up to now indicates that the helicopter was struck from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of the scattered aircraft remains suggests that the helicopter was impacted to the ground with its unsharpened structure.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft offer neither fire nor explosion at the site of the accident.
The final results of the investigation indicate several soil contactes.
On-site studies have found aircraft parts at an altitude of 9200 feet above sea level. The site is off-road and has a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter probably broke.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had several ground contacts.
After a minimal search in an area that went beyond the restricted area at the site of the accident, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, which reinforced the assumption that the unsaturated aircraft structure had been sprayed against the ground.
MSS announces a research protocol on the detection of the non-fatty gene
It is responsible for a research project on the detection of obesity in children and young people, supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Mexico Social Insurance Institute) announced that it is conducting a research project to discover the genetic markers of obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and youth", with which the genetic markers are to be found in conjunction with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, explained that an interdisciplinary team, consisting of doctors, nurses, nutrition specialists and social workers, was established.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate course at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and at the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested people can come to the IMSS sports facilities in the Mexico Valley, where every Saturday from 8.00 am tests are conducted with children and young people.
He stressed that the study began at Cuauhtémoc sports ground (in the west of the state of México) and continued on the Nezahualcóyolt sports ground (in the east of the state of México) since 8 October.
When the target is reached from 500 to 600 subjects, the study will continue on the Independencia sports ground (in the south of the capital district) and will be completed on the Morelos (north of the capital district).
He explained that the objective of the study was to identify factors and the role of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases for children and adolescents.
On the global day of diabetes, he explained that it is hoped that three thousand children and young people aged six to 14 should complete, with the consent of and under the supervision of their parents, nutrition-related questionnaires.
You will also be asked questions about their physical activity and family history of illness to control risk factors that could result in diabetes or kidney failure.
In addition, it showed that on those Saturdays the subjects were measured (weight, size, waist circumference), their blood pressure was controlled and blood levels such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (trying to identify genes associated with childhood obesity) were determined.
Cruz López stressed that this study would be carried out on the basis of the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"Health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years, the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent. The obesity was also dramatically increased," said IMSS specialist.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico was different from that of other peoples.
He stated that an average Mexican (e) represented 65 percent Indian-American, 30% European and 5% African descent, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he stated that the genetics of obesity were inability to burn the excess of energy (calories) taken to us, so that it would be stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the investigator was in a comprehensive examination of the children, which would determine whether they had a degree of obesity or obesity.
It would even examine the occurrence of dark skin folds in the neck and the inner arm (acanthosis), indicating the likelihood of metabolic disorders and diabetes in the pre-stage.
All information would be treated confidentially and notified to the parents by the doctors in writing. The doctors explain to the parents all the measurement results and suggest changes in the lifestyle that are appropriate to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there were three basic factors responsible for obesity, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, i.e. lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, that is, increased consumption of sugared drinks and carbohydrates (Tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) together with a high fat and protein intake as well as the genetics to be analyzed in this research project.
