Mr. Najera thought that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as some cities in the north of the country, in order to improve the behaviour of the pavement and thus avoid the appearance of impact holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound of which a part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalt - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes. Together they give the pavement its characteristic zähelastic behavior.
Wheatastic behaviour of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is highly viscous and almost fixed at 50°C, while it is brewing at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not the same, but changes one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature changes," the chemical engineer explained.
The researcher of the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had mostly a flexible pavement composed of six layers of material, including the last three asphalts.
Between the top layers lies a layer of asphalt, which consists of small, asphalted and then fortified stones.
Each stone of this layer of wear has been bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles are moved on and forces are generated, this layer enables a good distribution of forces in the street floor.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the layer of wear," he explained, "a last layer will be laid out, the so-called layer of leather, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. of sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they must produce friction.
Those that receive and distribute most of the forces of this road cover also require adequate thickness and material from which they are made must be maintained.
The weather conditions, in particular humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, above all the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the site becomes wet, water penetrates the layer and occurs only difficult again. This causes a softening of all layers of the pavement and consequently the appearance of impact holes.
When a blowhole occurs," he said, "the cover layer will first be removed, while the wear layer will only be affected after that. However, the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that must be maintained with the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) explained that the vehicle load is another important cause for the occurrence of impact holes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road covering must always be in proportion to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is respected in order to avoid frequent impact holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that many research projects were still awaited, for example, via asphalt emulsions, which were even on the market in other countries, with which the impact holes could be repaired easily and without the use of high temperatures.
