Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Northern Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the Baltic Sea seabed and connects Western Europe directly to Russia, has been put into operation.
It is intended to provide gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to do this event with glory and glory.
Over 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended last Tuesday on the Baltic Sea Coast under orchestral sounding and fine taster buffet the inauguration of the new Northern Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly under the sea level.
The German chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon, and his colleague Mark Rutte from the Netherlands, symbolically combined with the wheel of the valve, which carries the Russian gas into the Western European network.
With the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year will be delivered to Western Europe through a first pipeline of 1,224 km length, linking the Saint Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - the equivalent of French total consumption - will be completed by the end of 2012.
And you already let the eventuality of the construction of a third line ring on your own route.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this huge building seems like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream pipeline will enable direct gas delivery to Germany, avoiding any trassage by third countries (Poland or Ukraine) on the country road.
For this reason, these two countries lose a little of their power: for them it is now more difficult to exert pressure on Russia by threatening to conclude access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most strongly engaged in the debate, was not back in time to compare the North Stream pipeline with a "new German-Swietchen Pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically extremely sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply through the support of this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of strengthening European energy, as the project has struck a break between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In almost five years, Russia has completed its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, western countries, which have strong gas consumption and whose gas deposits are negated.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically," confirmed François Fillon at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out to what extent the large gas contracts are also important from political and economic sides.
All this explains the broad smile of the Gazprom managers representing many gas lines in Lubmin.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an excellent technique.
The underwater pipeline consists of steel with concrete coating which is intended to protect it from anchors.
It rests on the sea floor, at about 200 m depth.
In its construction, minefields dating from World War II had to be eliminated.
"Some hundreds of mines had to be carefully removed or destroyed," said Jens Müller, spokesperson of the Nord Stream Society.
In addition, reinforced measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long hose made of metal, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which has been interrupted by nothing over the entire length: neither by valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was provided for off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers have waived because the Swedes were not keen to see a Russian state company permanently located at the level of their coasts.
"In the case of a havari, we close the gas flow in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In the event of leaks, the gas contained in the gas pipeline will escape into the air.
However, this case is considered by the constructors to be little likely, since the welding seams were estimated to be a resistance of one leak per 100,000 years.
The state monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured by both an underwater robot controlled for external observation by a seagoing vessel and by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, measuring one metre diameter, is introduced into the inside of the pipeline and moved through the gas pressure.
After three complete days of movement through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on possible metal deformations upon arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo only the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is guaranteed simply by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
In addition, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated (each to 15.5%), as are the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (each to 9%).
These five companies have formed a group of companies called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom has then rented out the entire capacity of its gas transport on the renewable Twentieth-Year Treaty.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real transporter's amount of gas falls off," explained Jens Müller.
The financing of gas pipelines was secured to 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labour cost should be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, minority shareholders are willing to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone carries the liability risk.
The gas pipeline rises on a sandy coastal stretch with pine trees forested by Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5 metre high valves form the gas outlet platform.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other indicators of the incoming gas before it is transmitted to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been delivered with a million cubic meters of Russian gas per hour.
With full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic metres per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Founded about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine now wants to restore new style to writing.
It has a flair of adventure, with candlelight spent hours writing.
The notebook of Moleskine is easily recognizable, with its black, rectangular cover, its rubber band, the eggshell-colored sides, as it has aged over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook, as you know today, was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, which is based in Milan, decided at the time to place a distincted design notebook on the market.
Maria Sebregondi, then the company's specialist consultant, is responsible for the market launch of the new product.
The notebook was inspired by an old production technique called Mole Skin (Maulwurfskin), which refers to a cotton bag, which is used, for example, for covering upholstery benches.
This kind of notebook was very popular among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten subject, which until the 20th century was considered an icon of avant-garde artist," explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand-responsor at Modo Modo.
Success begins.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales are increasing by 26% and are building up with a sales of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first years in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine passes the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to make a phantom picture of buyers, as the notebook inspires business people as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultured and open minded customers.
The small Italian company, which was 12 employees in its early years, employs over 100 employees today and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan, the other in New York.
The company distributes its notebooks in bookstores, on Internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques of city centers and is committed to enforcing its identity.
"We have followed the spirit of time and its new need for writing, which exists despite the upswing of the e-mails," explained Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trajectory is accompanied by the development of Moleskine: Recently, the brand launched an exhibition called "Detour (Umweg)", in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a Leopards-designed cover on the occasion of the film festival in Locarno.
Moleskine benefited from his success and cultural spirit and understood it to diversify his products: bags, calendars, fillers, computer cases... The brand shows the entire range of articles.
A success that brings envy to the plan: In autumn 2006, Modo Modo was bought up by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, which opened a new chapter in the history of Moleskine.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today the "15th week of work for disabled people" begins.
Despite a targeted public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate in disabled people is always twice as high as the average average: 19% against 9% of the total population.
Depressing?
"No, this is how Éric Blanchet, Director-General of the Association of Adapt, emphasizes the "week of work for the disabled".
"The progress made within fifteen years is considerable."
"At that time the unemployment rate was not double, but triple that high."
"Not so much remains to be done."
It must be said, however, that for disabled people, there are still many obstacles before they get a job.
It is more common for the elderly: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualifications: 80% of them have no Abitur and there are only 10,000 people with disabilities among the 2.3 million students with higher education.
In conclusion, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% in the disabled, compared with 38% in the total.
In short, there are so many criteria which make it difficult to start work again and which make up the "core of the problem", says Christian Grapin, Director-General of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992, which helps companies to recruit disabled workers.
So much for the practical brakes.
Keep the unspoken, the mental attitudes, which, while certain, but slowly evolve.
A study carried out in April by the Association of IMS Entrepreneurs for the journal La Cité stated that the managers interviewed have "a weak level of knowledge regarding the disabled", which is "overrepresented" by persons in wheelchairs, mental or intellectually disadvantaged".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the employment objective of 6% disabled workers, as laid down in a 1987 law.
These latter figures, dating from 2008, refer to a quota of 2.6%.
"We are now in charge of 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, of the organisation responsible for making contributions from companies that disregard this law.
Proof: The number of "paying" establishments has decreased as well as the sum of the amounts paid between 2007 and 2011, ranging from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which provides for increased contributions, created a strong pressure on the companies," Pierre Blanc explained."
"But this improvement also gives a real insight, especially among the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of the establishments employ between 20 and 49 disabled persons, while companies with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
